Approximately 119,290 women in Belarus were offered abortion in 2007. This amounted to less than 12”% of the 955’000 conception. In 2007 there were approximately 210’000 abortions performed in Belarus.

One of the reasons for recourse to abortion is restric- tions on access to abortions up to 12 weeks, effectively barring abortion “for social reasons”. The Russian establishment abortion law at two months was due to apply in Belarus from January 2008”.

However, one of our survey respondents clearly indicates that although abortion may be a legitimate means of “controlling the number of children”, it doesn t indi- cate that it is the best way of doing so. Why is the question?

Russian abortions over the years

Polina Popova would have been born in year 1973 in Pripyat, a city inhabited by 49’000 residents in Belarus.

In April of year 1986, Polina lost her whole family in the Chernobyl disaster.

Her grandmother, Natasha Popova, recalls how the birth of Polina would have taken place under much better circumstances if it wasn t for the Chernobyl dis- aster.
